name: Backup

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  backup:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    timeout-minutes: 25
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Repository
        uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          repository: ${{ secrets.BACKUP_REPO }}
          token: ${{ secrets.ACCESS_TOKEN }}

      - name: Setup Node
        uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with:
          node-version: '20'

      - name: Run Backup
        run: |
          cd /tmp
          git clone -q https://github.com/everruler12/roam2github.git roam2github
          cd roam2github
          npm i
          npm run backup -s
        env:
          ROAM_EMAIL: ${{ secrets.ROAM_EMAIL }}
          ROAM_PASSWORD: ${{ secrets.NEW_ROAM_PASSWORD }}
          ROAM_GRAPH: ${{ secrets.ROAM_GRAPH }}
          BACKUP_EDN: true
          BACKUP_JSON: true
          BACKUP_MARKDOWN: true
          MD_REPLACEMENT: _

        uses: everruler12/git-auto-commit-action@v4

What does the q option here do: git clone -q https://github.com/everruler12/roam2github.git

---

_**Agent**_

The `-q` option in the `git clone` command stands for "quiet." When you use this option, Git suppresses most of the output that it would normally display during the cloning process. This can make the output less verbose and easier to read, especially in automated scripts or CI/CD pipelines.

Here's the command in context:
```sh
git clone -q https://github.com/everruler12/roam2github.git roam2github
```

This command will clone the repository `https://github.com/everruler12/roam2github.git` into a directory named [`roam2github`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%22%22%2C%5B%7B%22uri%22%3A%7B%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%2C%22authority%22%3A%22%22%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Fc%3A%2FUsers%2Fscott%2Fsrc%2Frepos%2Froam-book-research-backup-actions%2F.github%2Fworkflows%2Fmain.yml%22%2C%22query%22%3A%22%22%2C%22fragment%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%22pos%22%3A%7B%22line%22%3A29%2C%22character%22%3A54%7D%7D%5D%2C%2204d4bba9-5add-4fc7-bfbf-c3853c488cd8%22%5D "Go to definition") with minimal output.
